term.gif" align=absmiddle>  Re: Nuclear thermal rocket accidents.</span><hr size=1> we have extremely reliable ways of creating fusion, and we do it all the time.<br>
<br>
creating fusion is not the issue.  creating energy-efficient fusion, with magnetically confined plasma and adequate thermal shielding, is the real issue.<br>
<br>
fusion is getting better each year tho.  current plans for fusion space drives are for fusion-antimatter hybrid drives, where antiprotons are used in antimatter annihilation reactions to provide the energy needed to trigger the fusion reactions in the fuel.<br>
<br>
this hybrid drive is already being worked on as we speak by NASA, as are fission drives. <p></p><i></i></td></tr><tr bgcolor=#333333><td nowrap width=20% valign=top align=left><span class=title> <A HREF=http://pub97.ezboard.com/uprojectorion.showPublicProfile?language=EN>projectorion</A></span><br> <span class=usertitle>Nuclear Renaissance Man</span><br>  Posts: 1715<br> <font color=#6F6F6F>(7/29/02 11:05 pm)</font><br>   <a href=http://pub97.ezboard.com/fnuclearspacefrm4.showAddReplyScreenFromWeb?topicID=126.topic&index=8>Reply</a>   </td><td valign=top align=left class=m><span class=title> <img src="http://www.nuclearspace.com/ezboard/images/posticons/7.gif" align=absmiddle>  Reactors.</span><hr size=1> Plant reactors operate 24 hours a day for decade after decade with rarely if ever any incident. The chances of a reactor failure therefore seem negligible during the few minutes of flight time necessary to get off planet. Far less likely than the 1 in 10 failures known to happen with chemical. This alone makes nuclear far safer. <p></p><i></i></td></tr><tr bgcolor=#484848><td nowrap width=20% valign=top align=left><span class=title> <A HREF=http://pub97.ezboard.com/ubrp17.showPublicProfile?language=EN>brp17</A></span><br> <span class=usertitle>NERVA Spaceplane Pilot</span><br>  Posts: 107<br> <font color=#6F6F6F>(7/30/02 8:33 am)</font><br>   <a href=http://pub97.ezboard.com/fnuclearspacefrm4.showAddReplyScreenFromWeb?topicID=126.topic&index=9>Reply</a>   </td><td valign=top align=left class=m><span class=title> <img src="http://www.nuclearspace.com/ezboard/images/posticons/7.gif" align=absmiddle>  Re: Reactors.</span><hr size=1> PO, I think your figures are a bit obscure. 1 in 10 may be true, but that's over a large period of time, probably since the begining of the space race. A better way would be to look at the space shuttles, which have had over a hundred launches and only 1 failure.<br>
<br>
Also, launching from space is very different than having a reactor on the ground. You need a lighter reactor, which invites danger more easily. Still, it is pretty reliable, but remember, I think there's only been 1 or 2 real nuclear reactors into space, the rest were RTG's. It's very different to put them in 0 g, I think right now there's only a handful of reactors that would work well in 0 g, the number 5 comes to mind. The best reactor for space I believe is the centripital reactor, I don't know the workings of it, but a friend of mine whose a nuclear scientist explained it to me one time, the problem was her english is limited, and I just got the impression that it spins around somehow, but not the whole thing. Might be worth looking into more. <p></p><i></i></td></tr><tr bgcolor=#333333><td nowrap width=20% valign=top align=left><span class=title> <A HREF=http://pub97.ezboard.com/uprojectorion.showPublicProfile?language=EN>projectorion</A></span><br> <span class=usertitle>Nuclear Renaissance Man</span><br>  Posts: 1746<br> <font color=#6F6F6F>(8/1/02 11:35 pm)</font><br>   <a href=http://pub97.ezboard.com/fnuclearspacefrm4.showAddReplyScreenFromWeb?topicID=126.topic&index=10>Reply</a>   </td><td valign=top align=left class=m><span class=title> <img src="http://www.nuclearspace.com/ezboard/images/posticons/7.gif" align=absmiddle>  Re: Reactors.</span><hr size=1> Why use a standard reactor? For launching a rocket a taylor made version would be best. Something like NERVA. Today's technology could probably manage 1000 Isp. Helium is one option for safe propellant. There are probably others. Separating power from propellant has never been fully explored. Once in space it could even switch over to a second more efficient but lower thrust reactor. Perhaps Americium foil based.<br>
<br>
Anti-matter triggered fusion pulse rockets would be great if we could build them but the technology is still a fair way off. Same as laser triggered fusion. A pity. I could imagine an Orion carrying onboard reactors to power a multi-megawatt laser. <br>
